source.description: A corporate body that belongs to the EU or to one of its predecessors.
An international organization is an organization with an international membership, scope, or presence.
An organisation that does not belong to the EU or to one of its predecessors, nor has an international membership, scope, or presence.
The institutions of the European Union are the seven principal decision making bodies of the European Union. They are listed in Article 13 of the Treaty on European Union.
A European Union corporate body that collaborates with the EU institutions playing an advisory or other specialised role.
The interinstitutional services are under governance of EU institutions and bodies and are attached administratively to the European Commission.
A EU joint undertaking is a public-private partnership between the European Union and private companies.

An agency of the European Union is a decentralised body of the European Union, which is distinct from the institutions and bodies. Agencies are established to accomplish specific tasks. Each agency has its own legal personality.
Agencies created by a specific legislative act and charged with a particular task.

Legal entities established in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 58/2003 (OJ L 11, 16.1.2003) with a view to being entrusted with certain tasks relating to the management of one or more European Union programmes. These agencies are set up for a fixed period.
A European Union agency which cannot be classified as decentralised, executive, Euratom, or common foreign and security policy agency.
Agencies which have been created to support the aims of the European Atomic Energy Community Treaty (Euratom).

source.description: Decentralised agencies which have been created to support the common foreign and security policy of the European Union or its predecessors.
The European Commission has offices, called Representations, in all the Member States of the European Union.
The European External Action Service has delegations worldwide to represent the European Union's diplomatic interests.
The European Parliament has information offices in all the Member States of the European Union.
A Directorate-General is the highest level of administrative division at the European Commission.
A Directorate is the second highest level of administrative division at the European Commission.
A Joint Committee is a body established in a bilateral agreement between the EU (or its predecessors) and a third country or organisation.

An Association Council is a body established in a bilateral agreement between the EU (or its predecessors) and a candidate or Euro-Mediterranean partnership country to monitor the implementation of the association agreement.
A Cooperation Council is a body established in a bilateral agreement between the EU and a partner country to monitor the implementation of the agreement.

description.p: European Parliament Members are divided up among a number of specialised standing committees. The committees draw up, amend and adopt legislative proposals and own-initiative reports. They consider Commission and Council proposals and, where necessary, draw up reports to be presented to the plenary assembly. The political make-up of the committees reflects that of the plenary assembly.

Parliament can also set up sub-committees and special temporary committees to deal with specific issues, and is empowered to create committees of inquiry to investigate alleged contraventions or maladministration of EU law.

source.description: The Members of the European Parliament sit in political groups organised by political affiliation. 25 Members are needed to form a political group, and at least one-quarter of the Member States must be represented within the group. Members may not belong to more than one political group. Some Members do not belong to any political group and are known as non-attached Members.
An EP Directorate-General is the highest level of administrative division at the European Parliament.

Separate commissions (groups of Members) prepare the opinions of the Committee of the Regions in response to proposed new legislation by the European Commission. The composition of each Commission reflects the political and national composition of the CoR.
The members of the Committee of the Regions have formed groups which reflect their political affiliations. Each group has its own secretariat.
A Directorate is the highest level of administrative division at the Committee of the Regions.

source.description: A Stabilisation and Association Council is a body established in a bilateral agreement between the EU and a Western Balkan country to monitor the implementation of the stabilisation and association agreement.
The European Parliament has liaison offices in all the Member States of the European Union and one in the United States.
A service department which deals with particular administrative issues.
